Bank Churn Prediction

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

Businesses like banks which provide service have to worry about problem of 'Customer Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Objective¶

You as a Data scientist with the bank need to build a neural network based classifier that can determine whether a customer will leave the bank or not in the next 6 months.

Data Dictionary¶

  • CustomerId: Unique ID which is assigned to each customer

  • Surname: Last name of the customer

  • CreditScore: It defines the credit history of the customer.

  • Geography: A customers location

  • Gender: It defines the Gender of the customer

  • Age: Age of the customer

  • Tenure: Number of years for which the customer has been with the bank

  • NumOfProducts: refers to the number of products that a customer has purchased through the bank.

  • Balance: Account balance

  • HasCrCard: It is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer has credit card or not.

  • EstimatedSalary: Estimated salary

  • isActiveMember: Is is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer is active member of the bank or not ( Active member in the sense, using bank products regularly, making transactions etc )

  • Exited : whether or not the customer left the bank within six month. It can take two values 0=No ( Customer did not leave the bank ) 1=Yes ( Customer left the bank )

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

# function to plot stacked bar chart

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()
In [638]:
### Function to plot distributions

def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Model Building¶

Model Evaluation Criteria¶

Model can make wrong predictions as:

  1. False Positive/Precision: When model predicting that a customer will Chrun but in real case the customer will not Churn - This leads to loss of resources
  2. False Negative/Recall: When model predicting a customer will not churn but in real case the customer was going to churn - This leads to loss of opportunity

Which case is more important?

  • For Bank case scenario losing a potential customer by predicting that the customer will not be churn but in reality the customer was going to churn.

How to reduce this loss i.e need to reduce False Negatives or increase Recall?

Model Evaluation criteria

  • Bank would want Recall to be maximized, greater the Recall higher the chances of minimizing false negatives. Hence, the focus should be on increasing Recall or minimizing the false negatives.

Let's create a function for plotting the confusion matrix¶

In [675]:
def plot_confusion_matrix(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    threshold=0.5

    # Predict the target values using the provided model and predictors
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors) > threshold
    #y_pred = model.predict(predictors)

    # Compute the confusion matrix comparing the true target values with the predicted values
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)

    # Create labels for each cell in the confusion matrix with both count and percentage
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)    # reshaping to a matrix

    # Set the figure size for the plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))

    # Plot the confusion matrix as a heatmap with the labels
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")

    # Add a label to the y-axis
    plt.ylabel("True label")

    # Add a label to the x-axis
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

def plot(history, name):
    """
    Function to plot loss/accuracy

    history: an object which stores the metrics and losses.
    name: can be one of Loss or Accuracy
    """
    fig, ax = plt.subplots() #Creating a subplot with figure and axes.
    plt.plot(history.history[name]) #Plotting the train accuracy or train loss
    plt.plot(history.history['val_'+name]) #Plotting the validation accuracy or validation loss

    plt.title('Model ' + name.capitalize()) #Defining the title of the plot.
    plt.ylabel(name.capitalize()) #Capitalizing the first letter.
    plt.xlabel('Epoch') #Defining the label for the x-axis.
    fig.legend(['Train', 'Validation'], loc="outside right upper") #Defining the legend, loc controls the position of the legend.
In [678]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using statsmodels
def model_performance_classification(
    model, predictors, target, threshold=0.5
):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    threshold: threshold for classifying the observation as class 1
    """

    # checking which probabilities are greater than threshold
    pred = model.predict(predictors) > threshold
    # pred_temp = model.predict(predictors) > threshold
    # # rounding off the above values to get classes
    # pred = np.round(pred_temp)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute F1-score

  # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1 Score": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

  • Let's start with a neural network consisting of
    • One Input Layer with 32 neurons
    • Two hidden layers with 16 and 8 neurons respectively
    • Activation function of ReLU.

In [700]:
#Initializing the neural network
model_nn_with_adam = Sequential()

# Adding the first input layer with 32 neurons and relu as activation function
model_nn_with_adam.add(Dense(32, activation='relu', input_dim = X_train.shape[1]))

# Adding the second input layer with 16 neurons and relu as activation function
model_nn_with_adam.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))

# Adding the second input layer with 8 neurons and relu as activation function
model_nn_with_adam.add(Dense(8, activation='relu'))

# Adding the output input layer sigmoid as activation function
model_nn_with_adam.add(Dense(1, activation = 'sigmoid'))

Neural Network with Balanced Data (by applying SMOTE) and SGD Optimizer¶

Let's try to apply SMOTE to balance this dataset and then again apply hyperparamter tuning accordingly.

  • Let's start with a neural network consisting of
    • One Input layer with 32 neurons respectively
    • Two hidden layers 16 and 8 neurons respectively
    • Activation function of ReLU.
    • SGD as the optimizer with learning_rate=0.001
    • Using Oversampled data set for training
In [736]:
#Initializing the neural network
model_nn_with_sgd_smote = Sequential()

# Adding the first input layer with 32 neurons and relu as activation function
model_nn_with_sgd_smote.add(Dense(32, activation='relu', input_dim = X_train_smote.shape[1]))

# Adding the second input layer with 16 neurons and relu as activation function
model_nn_with_sgd_smote.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))

# Adding the third input layer with 8 neurons and relu as activation function
model_nn_with_sgd_smote.add(Dense(8, activation='relu'))

# Adding the output input layer sigmoid as activation function
model_nn_with_sgd_smote.add(Dense(1, activation = 'sigmoid'))

Let's find the optimal threshold using the ROC-AUC curve

In [799]:
y_test_pred = model_nn_with_adam_smote_drop.predict(X_test)

# Step 1: Compute the ROC curve
fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_test_pred)

auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_test_pred)

# Step 2: Compute the distance to the top-left corner (0,1)
distances = np.sqrt((1 - tpr)**2 + (fpr)**2)

# Step 3: Find the threshold that minimizes the distance
optimal_idx = np.argmin(distances)
optimal_threshold = thresholds[optimal_idx]

# Step 4: Plotting the ROC curve
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label=f'ROC Curve (AUC = {auc:.2f})', color='b')

# Plot the random guess line (45 degree line)
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], linestyle='--', color='r', label='Random Guess')

# Set labels and title
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate (1 - Specificity)')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate (Sensitivity / Recall)')
plt.title('ROC Curve')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')

# Display the plot
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

print(f"\nOptimal threshold: {optimal_threshold}")

Optimal threshold: 0.5119040012359619

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

Actionable Insights:

  • Geography and Churn: Customers from Germany are more likely to churn compared to those from France and Spain. Targeting this region with improved services and retention strategies may reduce churn.

  • Gender and Churn: Female customers have a higher likelihood of leaving the bank compared to male customers. This may point to specific pain points or dissatisfaction that female customers experience more than males, requiring tailored retention strategies.

  • Customer Age: Customers in the age group of 32 to 45 years represent the bulk of the customer base. However, age does not show a strong correlation with churn, suggesting that retention strategies shouldn't focus on age-specific initiatives alone.

  • Tenure Impact: Customers with shorter tenures are more prone to churn. Offering early engagement programs, loyalty bonuses, and enhanced support for new customers (especially in their first few years) could help retain them.

  • Number of Products: Customers with 3 or more products have a higher probability of leaving. The bank should monitor high-product users closely, as they might feel overwhelmed or may not need all the services. Offering personalized advice on optimizing their product use could prevent churn.

  • Inactive Members: Inactive customers are significantly more likely to leave the bank. The bank should implement re-engagement campaigns for inactive members, such as personalized offers or reminders about the benefits of using bank services.

  • Credit Card Ownership: The presence of a credit card does not significantly impact churn rates. Therefore, promoting credit cards as a retention tool may not be effective. However, other products or services might have more influence.

  • Credit Score Irrelevance: Credit score does not appear to influence whether a customer leaves. Hence, using credit score alone to predict churn or target marketing efforts is not effective.

  • Balance and Salary Impact: Neither the account balance nor the estimated salary significantly affects churn rates. Therefore, wealthier customers are not necessarily more likely to remain loyal, and these variables should not be the sole focus of retention strategies.

Business Recommendations:

  1. Geography-Specific Retention Programs:

    • Focus on Germany by implementing targeted loyalty programs, offering specialized products, and providing improved customer service and feedback mechanisms.

  2. Female Customer Engagement:

    • Conduct surveys or research to understand why female customers have a higher churn rate and tailor marketing or service improvements to address their needs.
    • Create gender-specific offers or campaigns to boost engagement.

  3. Enhanced Onboarding for New Customers:

    • Provide personalized services and educational resources for customers with lower tenures to increase their engagement and reduce churn.
    • Implement loyalty programs or incentives for customers as they reach certain tenure milestones.

  4. Monitor and Assist High-Product Users:

    • Regularly check in with customers who own multiple products to ensure they are satisfied with their services and not overwhelmed.
    • Offer product consolidation or optimization strategies to prevent them from leaving due to product overload.

  5. Re-Engagement for Inactive Members:

    • Develop a program for inactive members that includes personalized reminders, offers for re-engagement, or exclusive services to encourage them to use the bank's services regularly.
    • Provide automated tools like spending analysis or financial health reports to inactive members as part of their bank account.

  6. Predictive Analytics for Early Churn Detection:

    • Use the neural network model to predict and flag high-risk customers before they churn, focusing especially on customers with multiple products, shorter tenures, and inactive accounts.
    • Develop intervention strategies (like personalized offers or customer service interactions) based on these predictions.

  7. Personalized Product Recommendations:

    • Leverage the data on product usage to offer customized product recommendations to customers. Ensure that recommendations are in line with their financial needs and usage patterns to prevent product overload and dissatisfaction.

  8. Customer Satisfaction and Feedback Mechanisms:

    • Regularly collect feedback from customers (especially in the first few years) to address their concerns early on.
    • Develop a "Voice of the Customer" program to prioritize customer satisfaction and take proactive measures based on feedback.

By implementing these insights and recommendations, the bank can significantly reduce churn and improve customer satisfaction and loyalty.
